A notable feature of Kōkadani Kofun is the presence of "bicycle-wheel-like patterns" ({{ill|双脚輪状文|ja|双脚輪状文|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/双脚輪状文|qq=}}) among its decorations. This motif is rare, with only four known examples nationwide.<ref>Other examples include {{ill|Kamao Kofun|ja|釜尾古墳|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kamao Kofun|qq=}} and {{ill|Yokoyama Kofun|ja|横山古墳|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yokoyama Kofun|qq=}} in Kumamoto Prefecture, and {{ill|Ōzuka Kofun|ja|王塚古墳|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōzuka Kofun|qq=}} in Fukuoka Prefecture.</ref> Additionally, the presence of a stone cist, which is a characteristic of burial facilities in the Higo region, suggests a strong connection between the kofun's Interred_individual and the Higo area.<ref name=iwato />
Based on features such as the single-chamber stone chamber, Kōkadani Kofun is estimated to have been constructed in the mid-6th century, slightly preceding the {{ill|Maruyama-tsuka Kofun (Yame)|lt=Maruyama-tsuka Kofun (Yame)|lt=Maruyamazuka Kofun (Yame)|ja|丸山塚古墳 (八女市)|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Maruyamazuka Kofun (Yame)|qq=}}.<ref name=iwato />
Today, Kōkadani Kofun is maintained as a park alongside the adjacent {{ill|Sekijinzan Kofun|ja|石人山古墳|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sekijinzan Kofun|qq=}}. The stone chamber is open to the public twice a year, in spring and autumn. A replica of the chamber is displayed at the nearby {{ill|Kofunpia Hirokawa|ja|こふんぴあ広川|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kofunpia Hirokawa|qq=}} facility.<ref>[https://www.town.hirokawa.fukuoka.jp/shisetsuguide/shisetsu_37.htm Kofunpia Hirokawa, Hirokawa Town]</ref>
